  "articleSummary": "The article argues that well‑crafted multiple‑choice questions are a powerful teaching tool because the distractors—carefully chosen wrong answers—reveal learners’ mental models and misconceptions, turning the quiz itself into a diagnostic lesson. Using programming examples (e.g., a PostgreSQL identity‑column question), the author shows how each wrong option can target specific misunderstandings across skill levels, and how designing such options forces authors to clarify the core concept they intend to teach. The piece is aimed at educators, technical writers, and content creators who build quizzes or instructional material, and it adopts an analytical, tutorial‑style tone that repeatedly frames MCQs as “curriculum‑building” rather than mere assessment.",
